<br>
Also, i dont want people thinking i am trying to lecture them.  I am trying to create dialog, and also get some information out to some of our younger lanys enchanters who might be &quot;lurking&quot; but not posting on our boards.  I really like to think that Lanys enchanters are some of the best ( if not the best ) around, and only by sharing info will we remain that way.<br>
<br>
Todays topic is &quot;managing your group&quot;.  Elder enchanters know that enchanters tend to become the &quot;defacto&quot; leaders of a group, along with the group puller.  It is these two individuals that control the flow of mobs the the group, and also indirectly the speed at which the group kills.  I would like to talk about some of the things &quot;I&quot; do in groups to help them be more efficient.  Please keep in mind that none of this is &quot; right&quot; or &quot;wrong&quot; but, it is how i like to do things, generally.<br>
<br>
1) When you enter a group, the first thing you should do ( after saying hello ), is cast clarity on your Healers / Buffers, then follow with clarity on your intell caster types, then your hybrids.<br>
<br>
Why ?  first, the very first thing these people will say to you is &quot; enchanter ? whoot clarity !&quot;, and they will tell you they dont have clarity if you dont start casting it in .5 seconds from joining the group.  Second, do the healer / buffer classes first, so THEY may get on with the business of buffing YOU ( and the rest of the group ).<br>
<br>
2) Identify who the main assist is.  You can generally tell how &quot; with it&quot; your group is by how fast they answer this question ( at lower levels ).  A statemnt like &quot; hiya how is everyone, thanks for the group invite !.. btw-- who is the main assist ?&quot; works.  While you are saying this, you should be casting clarity ( see point 1 above ).<br>
<br>
3) make sure you have all your appropriate self buffs on.  At the very least, you should have your personal shielding spell, and clarity.  Those are a given.  More than likely, you will also have your best Cha buff on, as well.  Any other self buffs are up to you. I keep Group Resist Magic on at all times, even while travelling.  I like to use AoE mezz on occasion, so i want my MR as high as possible.  please see &quot;Goshans topic of the day - AoE mezz&quot; for more information on this spell line.<br>
<br>
4) Haste your tanks.  This assumes you just joined the group, and they were waiting for you.    If Buffing yourself, Casting clarity on a heavy mana using group ( hybrid tanks, int casters etc ) and Hasting all your tanks will take you below 40m DONT haste all the tanks.. haste the main tank, and the rogue if you have one.  Tell the others you will get them as mana permits.  if you can squeeze all the buffs in and have 40 mana, then do so.<br>
<br>
5) BEFORE you move to your camp spot ( assuming dungeon hunting ), CHECK YOUR BUFF SCREEN.  At the very least you should have a couple buffs from your healer / buffers, depending on what class they are.  If you have a cleric, you should have :<br>
<br>
A buff from the Clerics Resolution Line ( HP / AC )<br>
A buff from the clerics Armor of Faith Line ( AC) <br>
<br>
If the group is a 50+ group, you should also have :<br>
<br>
A Buff from the cleric symbol line ( please note, it is not ALWAYS necessary to have the clerics best symbol.  Sometimes the cleric cant afford it, and some times the camp doesnt warrant it.  If you want to make sure you always get symbols, YOU should be prepared to carry the appropriate stones around as well to give to them.  IN the higher end game this is not necessary, as clerics get reimbursed out of the group funds for casting these spells.  If your cleric is using jasper symbols on you, make sure they are not getting all the gems in a 50+ group though ).<br>
<br>
If you have a Druid, make sure to get Skin Like ( XXX), provided there is no cleric around.<br>
<br>
If all you have is a shaman, DONT get their talisman line.  Only get Their AGI and STA buffs.  Their Talisman line doesnt stack with shielding series, and good shaman will know this by the time they can cast this line of spells.<br>
<br>
DONT proceed to your camp spot untill you feel comfortable with the status of your buffs, AND the status of your mana.  This doesnt mean you should buff everyone and med to full ( lord knows they wont give you that much time if the group is ready to go ), but, dont buff everyone and leave yourself 20 mana and then proceed to camp either.  Buff down to 40m, then med back to 50 or 60m.  DONT LET THEM RUSH YOU if your not ready.  Medding from 40m to 60 m will take 1-2 extra minutes.  That time is worth it if you have to stop trains right away.<br>
<br>
Now... your group is buffed, you are 60m, and you start moving to your camp spot.  If you are not actively mezzing mobs, you should be medding.  Your goal is to med back as close to full as you can while your group is progressing toward your camp spot.<br>
<br>
Listen to how much mana your cleric has.  It is YOUR job to help control mana flow from the cleric, and yourself, so that both of you are close to the same amount of mana.  it is BAD if the cleric is 90m + all the time because you are slowing every mob, and chain stunning, and you are constantly 30m and struggling to buff / crowd control.  It is also BAD if the reverse is true, and you are FM and your cleric is at 30m all the time.  here are some tips..<br>
<br>
If you have more mana than your cleric, slow every mob for a bit, and chain stun a mob or 2 so they do almost no damage to your tanks.  Your cleric will get almost un interrupted med time, and you will burn some of the mana you have.<br>
<br>
If the cleric has more mana than you, and they pull a sinlge mob, DONT slow it.  let it beat on the tank and save yourself the slow mana, ( and get some extra med time ), Your cleric will have to burn a little mana to heal the main tank, and you will balance mana.<br>
<br>
Your at camp, now what ?<br>
<br>
After you get to camp ( and break the room in one of those exciting &quot;enchanter moments &quot;), you settle into the routine of grinding experience.  your puller will begin pulling mobs based on how fast you are killing them ( hopefully, if they are good ) and make sure that just as you are killing one mob, they are bringing another.  If you are in a good group, you will have at least one mob in camp for the next several hours.  This means you need to space your buffs.  Remember , you buffed everyone with everything when you joined the group and it will ALL drop at the same time.  You need to space them out so they drop about 5 min apart, not all at once.  This is sort of more work for you, because you will basicially be buffing or crowd controlling constantly for the next several hours, but it is the only way to keep up.<br>
<br>
The best way to space buffs is to NEVER sit at fm.  When you break the camp, and are starting pulls, if you are 80m+ go ahead and refresh clarity.  I know it hasnt dropped yet, but , this saves those tells of ( clarity fade ) in the middle of trying to control 5 mobs.  5 minutes after you refresh clarity, refresh Resist magic ( or Group resist magic ).  5 minutes after that, refresh the haste on your tanks.  Whenever you find yourself with a surplus of mana , refresh some buffs on either yourself, or your group.  <br>
<br>
Keep a clock by the side of your computer if you need to, to keep track of how long your mezzes are going to last.  I time buffs by casting them on myself first ( except for haste ), then casting on the people to be buffed.  I dont time haste this way because it is simply too mana intensive, and you need to keep a mana reserve for crowd control.<br>
<br>
If you manage to balance this all correctly, you will very rarely have to tell your group ( OOM  !), unless you have to perform a miracle save.  You MUST always keep mana for these &quot;miracle saves&quot;.  That is what you are there for.  Enchanters in most dungeons are saftey nets.<br>
<br>
This is another one of my long posts, but if i emphasize one thing it would be to make sure you balance your mana with your healers mana, to keep your group opperating at peak efficiency.  If you are killing things too slow, consider charming a mob to use as a pet to aid in damage.  If your group is mowing through mobs, it is better you dont charm a mob and disrupt the flow of exp to your yellow bar.<br>
<br>
<br>
