<br>
For pre-camp buffing, it will often help you get started quicker if you offer to handle AC buffs instead of the cleric at least for the 1st buff round, using something like Umbra. Cleric AC buffs are *extremely* mana intensive, and for a full buffing round a cleric will run out of mana real fast. Just for comparison, my lower level cleric alt (lvl 40) takes 440 mana to fully buff each member in a group, with AC/Skin/Symbol lines of buffs, and thats at lvl 40. The AC line alone takes almost half of this mana. The lvl 49 ac buff Shield of Words takes a full 300 mana for a single buff, or about the same as your lvl 60 haste buff Visions of Grandeur (a bit more actually)... So AC buffs alone costs the cleric 1800 mana, add to this 420 for heroic bond and 1890 for best symbol, you have a cleric who's OOM twice over. If you can cover AC buffs for a bit, you're helping him out a LOT, and get started a lot faster <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  And though Umbra isn't as good as Shield of Words, it *is* a decent buff. And a whole lot cheaper.<br>
<br>
If the puller is a hybrid, clarity is simply a must for him. He will be the only caster in the group who *never* has any time to med, so he should be a high priority on your clarity list. Especially if he's also responsible for keeping up several buffs, such as rangers are often called upon to do (shameless self plug). Indeed, for most grouping situations that involve a ranger, he should be considered one of the buffers on equal terms with clerics, shamans and druids. If anyone wants me to elaborate on this, I will, but it'll get long so I wont do it right here. Resist magic is a must for the puller at the very least in any group, and of course for yourself. I can't count the times I've seen the message &quot;you resist Ensnaring Roots&quot; or &quot;you resist Tagars Insects&quot; and others while bringing a pull back. There are many casting mobs out there, and they always like to root the puller or something similarly nasty if he doesn't have the magic resistance to avoid it. Being rooted as a puller is not fun by the way <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  On the other hand, if you are running low on mana and have to choose who to haste, you can get away with leaving the puller out of the buff round. He'll be off pulling a lot of the time anyway rather than fighting, so it is not too great a loss of damage.<br>
<br>
About moving to the camp spot. Always wait for the puller to give the go ahead before you start moving, i've seen countless groups get wiped out or forced to pull a huge train to the nearest zone because someone who was *not* the puller decided it was time to move. For any and all decisions regarding movement, the pullers word is law. Before moving, a puller will clear out any static mobs and roamers on the way to the camp spot, or to a resting place in between where you can pull more mobs, to eventually get there. Rushing ahead without clearing out the area first will make your life as an enchanter a bit too exciting for comfort. It is seen everywhere, even in such easy dungeons as Karnors Castle, where the left moat group decides to take LCY and then promtly runs there without even considering that there might be 9 mobs in the way. If the try to do this, stop them, and let the puller do his job. Being in a hurry when moving is bad, a move needs to be controlled and well thought out. Ideally in this way, you will not have to fight anything until pulls begin at your new camp spot, except in instances where a regular break of the camp is required (monks, SKs or harmony usally mean it isn't, but they're not always available).<br>
<br>
About slowing mobs and mana levels... yep, totally agreed. It happens to be a pet peeve of mine when people just slow *everything* leaving them at low mana while the cleric never has to heal. <br>
<br>
A few things before I finish: Request of your puller to let you know if he's about to pull a big one, nothing like being prepared rather than suddenly seeing 5 mobs in camp. A good puller will do this without being asked, but not all pullers are good. Oh yes, and always keep enough mana for a miracle save, for when pullers like myself need to hit the social hotkey labeled &quot;O FUCK&quot;... (&quot;/g Oh shit... ready for a BIG one?&quot; followed by one of two others in my case... &quot;/g Incoming lots&quot; if the group is ready, or &quot;/g Going down, dont heal me&quot; to make sure the healers don't heal me if I have to eat it. And yes, I really do have those hotkeys, don't have time to type in situations like that <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> )<br>
<br>
PS. Some puller codes for number of mobs incoming that i've run into from many different people: &quot;1&quot; is a single mob, &quot;a few&quot; is 2 or 3, &quot;several&quot; is up to 5, &quot;lots&quot; is 6 or more. Seems to be pretty much general with the people i've grouped with. Easier than getting an exact count (if you stop to count them all you're dead), and fast to type even on the run. Of course, there's the last one which is simply &quot;zone&quot;... no explenation needed for that I think <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <p>Ulaian Moonleaf <BR>
56th outrider of Tunare <BR>
Leader, Avatars of Night</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#E5E5E6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/umiggent.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Miggent</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t d00d!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/5/01 11:44:16 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://mdr-nhl.home.att.net/chopra.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Enchanter Topic - managing groups.</span><hr size=1> Well, if you ever group with me you'll know to pretty much multiply whatever number I say by 2... &quot;one inc&quot; means I'll probably drag an add along the way, &quot;two inc&quot; means I likely have three or four coming, &quot;three inc&quot; means get ready cause it'll be tough, and when I say &quot;LOTS inc&quot; it means pray the evac gets off before everybody's dead <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
