<br>
Another thing you just mentioned is different people have different tastes in camp spots, which is entirely true. There are however a few criteria that one should strive to meet for a camp spot before deciding on it. A camp spot which lives up to all or some of these criteria will make it easier for the group to function as a whole. They are:<br>
<br>
1) Room to fight and maneuver (so rogues can get behind, enchanters space mezzed mobs ect)<br>
2) Line of sight along pulling paths close to camp (makes it possible to mez/root adds before they even reach camp)<br>
3) Centrally placed in the area of pulling (long pulls suck, and if too long can get the puller killed)<br>
4) No ledges, windows, bridges etc. that people can fall off (even if you don't agro a bunch of mobs, it may be hard to get back)<br>
5) Few or no roamers in the area (to reduce the number of unwanted adds)<br>
6) Few or no spawns in the area (same, but more dangerous since there is no warning)<br>
7) Ease of escape (if the shit hits the fan and you need to leave, fast)<br>
<br>
Often small changes in the placement of camp can determine whether it lives up to these or not, and so it can be worthwhile to consider a small move if a nearby site is more optimal. Usally the puller will do this on his own, but the puller will not always be familiar with the dungeon (camping a location and pulling to it are two different worlds, just having been to the camp does not mean you know the area around it. There is always a first time for pulling a camp) and good advice should always be welcome. Of the 7 points stated, #1 to #3 are by far the most important if you want the flow of exp to come fast and steady, #4 to #6 are not really a concern if you have a good group, and #7 is what coffins are for <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  (j/k)<br>
